            <div class="row text-center">
                <div class="col-md-12">

                    <p style="text-align:justify; margin-left:15%; margin-right:15%; font-size:20px;">
                        In 2012 and 2013, a Chinese scholar and member of an elite family unveiled 
                        approximately  250,000 Oriental artifacts dating back more than 8,000 
                        years ago.  It was during the Cultural Revolution when as a young boy, 
                        Yang Chang learned from his father about the stored artifacts. The boy 
                        went on to secure a strong education and learn the practice of Chinese 
                        medicine, curation of artifacts and ancient art forms. Today, the young 
                        boy, now Professor Yang Chang, has written several books on ancient art and 
                        the curation of artifacts.  A few years ago he expressed his desire to 
                        return all of the artifacts to the People of China.  The treasures had 
                        been hidden away  and preserved in caves stretching over a 20-mile 
                        range of mountains and had been preserved there over the decades to protect them from looters.
                        The recent archiving of the artifacts has already revealed fascinating 
                        new information impacting the history of China.
                    </p>
                    <br />
                    <p style="text-align:justify; margin-left:15%; margin-right:15%; font-size:20px;">
                        The People's Republic of China plans to build a total of 10 new 
                        museums in different locations throughout China to house the artifacts.
                        Two museums are already completed.  The first museum, the Tianjin Jade 
                        Buddha Palace, houses the jade treasures and Dr.
                        Yang Chang serves as the Head Curator. Professor Yang 
                        has a very good friend, Changdong Xu, who grew up in Shanghai with the 
                        current President of the People's Republic of China, Xi Jinping, holds 
                        both USA and Chinese citizenship for a more 
                        complete understanding of his role in China.  Mr. Xu helped Professor 
                        Yang unveil the artifacts and has
                        worked with Chinese Party officials to promote their preservation.
                   </p>
                    <br />
                     <p style="text-align:justify; margin-left:15%; margin-right:15%; font-size:20px;">
                       In order to expand the reach of  these artifacts and to help others around the PRC and the world who may never 
                        have the opportunity to physically visit one of the Jade Buddha Palace's in China, the China Institute of Orientalism 
                        furthers the work started by Professor Yang and Mr. Xu by presenting publicly available renderings of these invaluable 
                        artifacts. By providing renderings in a wide-range of formats, including 3-dimensional renderings, curated 
                        walk-throughs, virtual reality tours and 3-D models for printing, the China Institute of Orientalism is helping to 
                        establish a new standard for digital curation, leveraging modern technology to provide a remarkable window into ancient 
                        China for the people of the PRC and for the world.
                    </p>
